Docker Security — Non-Root User, Trivy Scan, Secrets

Why Docker Security Matters
Default container runs as root (UID 0)
    │
    ├─ Container escape → attacker gets root on HOST
    ├─ Secrets in ENV → visible in docker inspect, logs, history
    └─ Unscanned images → known CVEs ship to production

Step-by-Step Hands-On Practice
Step 1 — See the Problem: Root by Default

# What user does a container run as by default?
docker run --rm alpine whoami
# root  ← dangerous

docker run --rm alpine id
# uid=0(root) gid=0(root) groups=0(root)

# Root inside container = root on host if container escapes
# Prove it — root can read host files via bind mount
docker run --rm -v /etc:/host-etc alpine cat /host-etc/hostname
# Shows your HOST hostname — full read access as root

Step 2 — Add a Non-Root User in a Dockerfile
Dockerfile:
FROM node:20-alpine

WORKDIR /app

# Copy and install deps BEFORE switching user (needs write access)
COPY package*.json ./
RUN npm ci --omit=dev

COPY src/ ./src/

# Create a system group and user (no login shell, no home dir)
RUN addgroup -S appgroup && \
    adduser -S appuser -G appgroup

# Change ownership of app files to new user
RUN chown -R appuser:appgroup /app

# Switch to non-root user — all subsequent commands run as this user
USER appuser

EXPOSE 3000
CMD ["node", "src/index.js"]

# Build and verify
docker build -t secure-app:latest .
docker run --rm secure-app:latest whoami
# appuser  ✓

docker run --rm secure-app:latest id
# uid=100(appuser) gid=101(appgroup) groups=101(appgroup)

# Verify cannot write to system dirs
docker run --rm secure-app:latest sh -c "touch /etc/test 2>&1"
# touch: /etc/test: Permission denied  ✓

Step 3 — Non-Root for Different Base Images
# ── Alpine (addgroup/adduser) ─────────────────────────────────────────────────
RUN addgroup -S appgroup && adduser -S appuser -G appgroup
USER appuser

# ── Debian/Ubuntu (groupadd/useradd) ─────────────────────────────────────────
RUN groupadd --system appgroup && \
    useradd --system --gid appgroup --no-create-home appuser
USER appuser

# ── Using numeric UID directly (no name needed, K8s-friendly) ────────────────
RUN addgroup -S appgroup && adduser -S -u 10001 appuser -G appgroup
USER 10001     # numeric UID — works even without /etc/passwd in distroless

# ── Distroless (no shell, no package manager — most secure) ──────────────────
FROM gcr.io/distroless/nodejs20-debian12
COPY --from=builder /app /app
USER nonroot   # distroless has a built-in nonroot user (65532)
CMD ["/app/src/index.js"]

Step 4 — Read-Only Filesystem
# Run with read-only root filesystem
docker run --rm \
  --read-only \
  --tmpfs /tmp:rw,size=64m \       # allow writes only to /tmp (RAM)
  --tmpfs /var/run:rw,size=8m \    # allow PID files etc.
  secure-app:latest

# Any write outside /tmp or /var/run will fail
docker run --rm --read-only alpine sh -c "touch /etc/pwned 2>&1"
# touch: /etc/pwned: Read-only file system  ✓

In Docker Compose:
services:
  app:
    image: secure-app:latest
    read_only: true
    tmpfs:
      - /tmp:size=64m
      - /var/run:size=8m

Step 5 — Install Trivy
# Install Trivy (vulnerability scanner)
# Option 1: Script install
curl -sfL https://raw.githubusercontent.com/aquasecurity/trivy/main/contrib/install.sh | sh -s -- -b /usr/local/bin
# Option 2: Debian/Ubuntu (continued)
sudo apt-get update && sudo apt-get install -y trivy

# Option 3: Binary download
wget https://github.com/aquasecurity/trivy/releases/latest/download/trivy_Linux-64bit.tar.gz
tar -xzf trivy_Linux-64bit.tar.gz
sudo mv trivy /usr/local/bin/

# Verify
trivy --version

Step 6 — Scan Images with Trivy
# Scan a public image (shows all CVEs)
trivy image nginx:latest

# Filter by severity
trivy image --severity HIGH,CRITICAL nginx:latest

# Scan your own built image
trivy image secure-app:latest

# Output as JSON (useful for CI/CD parsing)
trivy image --format json --output results.json nginx:latest

# Scan and fail if CRITICAL found (use in CI pipeline)
trivy image --exit-code 1 --severity CRITICAL nginx:latest
echo $?   # 1 = critical found, 0 = clean

# Scan a tar file (offline — useful for CI artifacts)
docker save nginx:latest -o nginx.tar
trivy image --input nginx.tar

# Scan Dockerfile for misconfigurations
trivy config ./Dockerfile

# Scan for secrets baked into image
trivy image --scanners secret secure-app:latest

