Step 7 — Secrets: Never Bake Them In
# ── BAD: Secret in Dockerfile (permanent, visible in layers) ─────────────────
ENV DB_PASSWORD=supersecret123       # ← NEVER
RUN curl -H "Auth: mytoken" ...      # ← baked into layer history

# Prove the danger — even if you unset it in next layer, it's still there
docker history secure-app:latest
# Shows every RUN/ENV command including secrets

docker inspect secure-app:latest | grep -i password
# Can expose ENV secrets

# ── GOOD: Pass secrets at runtime ────────────────────────────────────────────
docker run --rm -e DB_PASSWORD="$DB_PASSWORD" secure-app:latest

# ── BETTER: Mount secret as file (not visible in env) ────────────────────────
docker run --rm \
  -v /run/secrets/db_password:/run/secrets/db_password:ro \
  secure-app:latest

# Inside app, read from file instead of env:
# password = open("/run/secrets/db_password").read().strip()

# ── BEST: BuildKit secret (never stored in any layer) ────────────────────────
# For secrets needed only at BUILD time (npm token, pip private registry, etc.)

# Dockerfile:
RUN --mount=type=secret,id=npm_token \
    NPM_TOKEN=$(cat /run/secrets/npm_token) npm install

# Build command:
DOCKER_BUILDKIT=1 docker build \
  --secret id=npm_token,src=$HOME/.npmrc \
  -t secure-app:latest .

Step 8 — Drop Linux Capabilities
# Default container has ~14 capabilities — drop all, add back only what's needed
docker run --rm \
  --cap-drop ALL \
  --cap-add NET_BIND_SERVICE \    # only if app needs ports < 1024
  secure-app:latest

# Check what capabilities a container has
docker run --rm alpine cat /proc/1/status | grep CapEff

# Common capabilities to always drop:
# CAP_SYS_PTRACE   — prevents strace/debug of other processes
# CAP_NET_ADMIN    — prevents network config changes
# CAP_SYS_ADMIN    — the most dangerous, almost root equivalent

Step 9 — Add Security Scanning to GitLab CI
# .gitlab-ci.yml
trivy_scan:
  stage: test
  image: aquasec/trivy:latest
  script:
    - trivy image --exit-code 0 --severity LOW,MEDIUM $CI_REGISTRY_IMAGE:$CI_COMMIT_SHA
    - trivy image --exit-code 1 --severity HIGH,CRITICAL $CI_REGISTRY_IMAGE:$CI_COMMIT_SHA
  allow_failure: false   # fail pipeline on CRITICAL/HIGH

All Interview Questions
Non-Root User
Question	Answer
Why not run as root in a container?	Container escape → attacker gets root on host
USER appuser vs USER 10001?	Numeric UID works without passwd, required by K8s runAsNonRoot
How do you verify non-root at runtime?	docker run --rm <image> whoami or id
What is distroless?	Image with no shell/package manager — smallest attack surface, uses UID 65532
What does chown -R appuser /app do in Dockerfile?	Transfers file ownership so non-root user can read/write app files

Trivy
Question	Answer
What does Trivy scan?	CVEs in OS packages + language libs, misconfigs, secrets
What is a CVE?	Unique ID for a known vulnerability, has CVSS severity score and a fixed version
How to fail CI on CRITICAL only?	trivy image --exit-code 1 --severity CRITICAL <image>
How to scan without internet?	docker save → tar → trivy image --input image.tar
Difference between trivy image and trivy config?	image scans a built image for CVEs; config scans IaC files (Dockerfile, K8s YAML) for misconfigurations
How to fix a HIGH CVE?	Rebuild with updated base image or pin upgraded package version

Secrets
Question	Answer
What's wrong with ENV SECRET=abc in Dockerfile?	Baked permanently into image layer — visible via docker history and docker inspect
How do you pass secrets to containers safely?	Runtime -e, mounted files, Docker secrets, Vault, K8s secrets
What is --mount=type=secret in BuildKit?	Build-time secret injected into a single RUN step only — never stored in any layer
Can you remove a secret from a published image?	No — layers are immutable. Must rebuild from scratch without the secret
How does Trivy detect secrets?	trivy image --scanners secret — scans file contents inside image layers for patterns like API keys, tokens, private keys

Read-Only & Capabilities
Question	Answer
What does --read-only do?	Makes root filesystem immutable — prevents malware from writing payloads
How do you allow writes in a read-only container?	--tmpfs /tmp mounts a RAM-based writable dir, discarded on exit
What is --cap-drop ALL?	Removes all Linux kernel capabilities — least privilege at kernel level
What capability does binding port 80 need?	CAP_NET_BIND_SERVICE
What is CAP_SYS_ADMIN?	Near-root kernel privilege — almost never needed, always drop it
